Trait description: Mean chromatogram peak, for a particular Cuticular Hydrocarbon (CHC). Data are originally displayed as a proportion from all CHCs detected. The name of each CHC can be deciphered as follows: linear alkanes are referred to by the abbreviation n-Cx, where ‘‘x’’ is the total carbon number. Methyl-branched alkanes are referred to with a y-Me-Cx prefix, where ’y’ is the carbon onto which the methyl group is bound. For example, 9-Me-C23 is a 23 carbon chain with a methyl on the 9th carbon. For monoenes (z-Cx:1) and dienes (z,z-Cx:2) the number of double bonds is indicated after the colon and the double bond position/s are ’z’ or ’z,z"). For example, 7-C23:1 has one double bond between the 7th and 8th carbons. Higher peaks indicate a greater amount of the CHC.
Title: Genetic architecture of natural variation in cuticular hydrocarbon composition in Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Mean chromatogram peak, for a particular Cuticular Hydrocarbon (CHC). Data are originally displayed as a proportion from all CHCs detected. Methyl-branched alkanes are referred to with a y-Me-Cx prefix, where ’y’ is the carbon onto which the methyl group is bound. For example, 9-Me-C23 is a 23 carbon chain with a methyl on the 9th carbon. For monoenes (z-Cx:1) and dienes (z,z-Cx:2) the number of double bonds is indicated after the colon and the double bond position/s are ’z’ or ’z,z"). For example, 7-C23:1 has one double bond between the 7th and 8th carbons. Higher peaks indicate a greater amount of the CHC.

The name of each CHC can be deciphered as follows: linear alkanes are referred to by the abbreviation n-Cx, where ‘‘x’’ is the total carbon number. Methyl-branched alkanes are referred to with a y-Me-Cx prefix, where ’y’ is the carbon onto which the methyl group is bound. For example, 9-Me-C23 is a 23 carbon chain with a methyl on the 9th carbon. For monoenes (z-Cx:1) and dienes (z,z-Cx:2) the number of double bonds is indicated after the colon and the double bond position/s are ’z’ or ’z,z"). For example, 7-C23:1 has one double bond between the 7th and 8th carbons. Higher peaks indicate a greater amount of the CHC.

The name of each CHC can be deciphered as follows: linear alkanes are referred to by the abbreviation n-Cx, where ‘‘x’’ is the total carbon number. Methyl-branched alkanes are referred to with a y-Me-Cx prefix, where ’y’ is the carbon onto which the methyl group is bound. For example, 9-Me-C23 is a 23 carbon chain with a methyl on the 9th carbon. For monoenes (z-Cx:1) and dienes (z,z-Cx:2) the number of double bonds is indicated after the colon and the double bond position/s are ’z’ or ’z,z"). For example, 7-C23:1 has one double bond between the 7th and 8th carbons. Higher peaks indicate a greater amount of the CHC.

Trait description: Mean pigmentation scores for tergite 5. Higher values indicate higher percentages of brown/black melanin on the tergite.
Authors: LM Dembeck, W Huang, MM Magwire…
Title: Genetic Architecture of Abdominal Pigmentation in Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Mean pigmentation scores for tergite 6. Higher values indicate higher percentages of brown/black melanin on the tergite.
Authors: LM Dembeck, W Huang, MM Magwire…
Title: Genetic Architecture of Abdominal Pigmentation in Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Mean wiggle index for third instar larvae 1 hour into exposure to 100ppm of imidacloprid, a neonicotinoid pesticide. The wiggle index measures the relative movement ratio for larvae before and after they were exposed to imidacloprid. Higher values indicate a smaller decrease in motility and therefore greater resistance to imidacloprid.
Authors: S Denecke, R Fusetto, F Martelli, A Giang, P Battlay…
Title: Multiple P450s and variation in neuronal genes underpins the response to the insecticide imidacloprid in a population of Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Mean wiggle index for third instar larvae 1 hour into exposure to 25ppm of imidacloprid, a neonicotinoid pesticide. The wiggle index measures the relative movement ratio for larvae before and after they were exposed to imidacloprid. Higher values indicate a smaller decrease in motility and therefore greater resistance to imidacloprid.
Authors: S Denecke, R Fusetto, F Martelli, A Giang, P Battlay…
Title: Multiple P450s and variation in neuronal genes underpins the response to the insecticide imidacloprid in a population of Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Mean combined glucose content extracted from 5 adult flies that lacked a microbiome, after controlling for dry weight. All micro-organisms were purged from egg-surfaces via dechorionation and larvae were reared on sterile food. Higher values indicate higher glucose content.
Authors: AJ Dobson, JM Chaston, PD Newell, L Donahue…
Title: Host genetic determinants of microbiota-dependent nutrition revealed by genome-wide analysis of Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Mean combined glucose content extracted from 5 adult flies that possessed a microbiome, after controlling for dry weight. All micro-organisms were purged from egg-surfaces via dechorionation and larvae were reared on medium supplemented with Acetobacter pomorum, Acetobacter tropicalis, Lactobacillus brevis, Lactobacillus fructivorans and Lactobacillus plantarum. All are common commensal bacteria that make up a large proportion of the D. melanogaster microbiome. Higher values indicate higher glucose content.
Authors: AJ Dobson, JM Chaston, PD Newell, L Donahue…
Title: Host genetic determinants of microbiota-dependent nutrition revealed by genome-wide analysis of Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Mean change in the combined glucose content of 5 adult flies that possessed a microbiome compared with flies that lacked a microbiome, after controlling for dry weight. All micro-organisms were purged from egg-surfaces via dechorionation and larvae were reared either on sterile medium or on medium supplemented with Acetobacter pomorum, Acetobacter tropicalis, Lactobacillus brevis, Lactobacillus fructivorans and Lactobacillus plantarum. All are common commensal bacteria that make up a large proportion of the D. melanogaster microbiome. Higher values indicate that the addition of microbiota resulted in a higher glucose content. Note though that the presence of micriobiota on average decreased glucose content.
Authors: AJ Dobson, JM Chaston, PD Newell, L Donahue…
Title: Host genetic determinants of microbiota-dependent nutrition revealed by genome-wide analysis of Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Mean combined triglyceride (TAG) content after glycerol substraction extracted from 5 adult flies that possessed a microbiome, after controlling for dry weight. All micro-organisms were purged from egg-surfaces via dechorionation and larvae were reared on medium supplemented with Acetobacter pomorum, Acetobacter tropicalis, Lactobacillus brevis, Lactobacillus fructivorans and Lactobacillus plantarum. All are common commensal bacteria that make up a large proportion of the D. melanogaster microbiome. Higher values indicate higher TAG content.
Authors: AJ Dobson, JM Chaston, PD Newell, L Donahue…
Title: Host genetic determinants of microbiota-dependent nutrition revealed by genome-wide analysis of Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Mean combined dry weight of 5 adult flies that lacked a microbiome. All micro-organisms were purged from egg-surfaces via dechorionation and larvae were reared on sterile food. Higher values indicate heavier flies.
Authors: AJ Dobson, JM Chaston, PD Newell, L Donahue…
Title: Host genetic determinants of microbiota-dependent nutrition revealed by genome-wide analysis of Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Mean combined dry weight of 5 adult flies that possessed a microbiome. All micro-organisms were purged from egg-surfaces via dechorionation and larvae were reared on medium supplemented with Acetobacter pomorum, Acetobacter tropicalis, Lactobacillus brevis, Lactobacillus fructivorans and Lactobacillus plantarum. All are common commensal bacteria that make up a large proportion of the D. melanogaster microbiome. Higher values indicate heavier flies.
Authors: AJ Dobson, JM Chaston, PD Newell, L Donahue…
Title: Host genetic determinants of microbiota-dependent nutrition revealed by genome-wide analysis of Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Mean change in the combined dry weight of 5 adult flies that possessed a microbiome compared with flies that lacked a microbiome. All micro-organisms were purged from egg-surfaces via dechorionation and larvae were reared either on sterile medium or on medium supplemented with Acetobacter pomorum, Acetobacter tropicalis, Lactobacillus brevis, Lactobacillus fructivorans and Lactobacillus plantarum. All are common commensal bacteria that make up a large proportion of the D. melanogaster microbiome. Higher values indicate that the addition of microbiota had a greater positive effect on weight. Note that the presence of micriobiota on average increased dry weight.
Authors: AJ Dobson, JM Chaston, PD Newell, L Donahue…
Title: Host genetic determinants of microbiota-dependent nutrition revealed by genome-wide analysis of Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Mean survival 48 hours after exposure to deltamethrin, a pyrethroid pesticide. Higher values indicate greater resistance to deltamethrin.

Trait description: Fecundity was estimated every other week of the female’s lifespan as a 2-day total of eggs laid, when living with a single standard male, at 25C. Trait description: Rapid cold hardening; a type of phenotypic plasticity that allows ectotherms to quickly enhance cold tolerance in response to brief chilling (lasting minutes to hours). This was measured by exposing one group of flies to a mild pre-treatment temperature (4 degrees C) before exposing them to a cold temperature (-6 degrees C), while another group of flies was immediately exposed to the cold temperature. RCH = prop survival after hardening – prop survival without hardening. These flies were reared at 25C and RCH was measured when adults were 28-days old. Higher values indicate a greater plastic response.
Title: Antagonistic pleiotropy and mutation accumulation contribute to age-related decline in stress response

Trait description: Rapid cold hardening; a type of phenotypic plasticity that allows ectotherms to quickly enhance cold tolerance in response to brief chilling (lasting minutes to hours). This was measured by exposing one group of flies to a mild pre-treatment temperature (4 degrees C) before exposing them to a cold temperature (-6 degrees C), while another group of flies was immediately exposed to the cold temperature. RCH = prop survival after hardening – prop survival without hardening. These flies were reared at 18C. Higher values indicate a greater plastic response.
Title: Constraints, independence, and evolution of thermal plasticity: Probing genetic architecture of long- and short-term thermal acclimation
Notes: Shares some data with Gerken, Eller and Morgan (2014). This is a more complete dataset, so perhaps we inlcude this rather than the Gerken, Eller and Morgan (2014) data.

Reference: Gerken, Eller and Morgan (2014) PhD thesis
Trait description: Estimated mean time from eclosion to laying an egg (days), when reared under fluctuating temperature controlled conditions, with a mean of 16.8C ± 6. Females cohabited a food vial with two males from the same DGRP line as the female. Calculated as T= Σ(lxmx)/R0, where lx = the proportion of females surviving each day, mx = the number of eggs laid each day and R0 is the net reproductive rate (or replacment rate). Higher values indicate a longer generation time. Note that this trait should be treated as a characteristic of a population, rather than that of an individual genotype.
Title: Genomics and physiological evolution of cold tolerance in Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Lambda. Population growth rate or intrinsic rate of increase. Defined as e^r, where r = ln(net reproductive rate) / generation time. Populations consisted of one female and two males from the same DGRP line. Note that this trait should be treated as a characteristic of a population, rather than that of an individual genotype.

Trait description: Mean fertilised egg retention score. An estimation of the progression of embryo development taken two hours after a one hour egg laying period. Higher values indicate more developed embryos which signifies a greater degree of egg retention. Note that both males and femlaes were sourced from the DGRP line, therefore variation could be explained by either the male or female genotype.
Title: The genetics of egg retention and fertilization success in Drosophila: One step closer to understanding the transition from facultative to obligate viviparity

Trait description: Proportion of unfertilised eggs produced by 3-4 flies that had been allowed to mate for at least two days beforehand. Note that flies were kept in population cages that contained both sexes from the same line during the mating period. This means that genetic variance in this trait variation could be explained by either the male or female genotype. Higher values indicate a greater proportion of unfertilised eggs.
Title: The genetics of egg retention and fertilization success in Drosophila: One step closer to understanding the transition from facultative to obligate viviparity

Trait description: Mean difference in startle response between flies reared on medium supplemented with medione sodium bisulfite (MSB; 3 mM concentration) and flies reared on standard medium. Calculated as the difference between control and MSB conditions, divided by the population mean difference between control and MSB conditions. MSB facilitates oxidative stress induced mortality. Higher values indicate a greater sensitivity to oxidative stress and a more compromised startle response.

Trait description: Mean phosphate/oxygen ratio (P:O ratio) - a measure of the efficiency with which mitochondria convert oxygen into ATP. The ratio was here calculated as the amount of ADP consumed per oxygen being reduced during state 3 respriation. Mitochondria were sourced from the thorax and respiration was measured in vitro. Higher values indicate more efficient ATP production.
Authors: P Jumbo-Lucioni, S Bu, ST Harbison, JC Slaughter…
Title: Nuclear genomic control of naturally occurring variation in mitochondrial function in Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Mean phosphate/oxygen ratio (P:O ratio) - a measure of the efficiency with which mitochondria convert oxygen into ATP. The ratio was here calculated as the amount of ADP consumed per oxygen being reduced during state 3 respriation. Mitochondria were sourced from the thorax and respiration was measured in vitro. Higher values indicate more efficient ATP production.
Authors: P Jumbo-Lucioni, S Bu, ST Harbison, JC Slaughter…
Title: Nuclear genomic control of naturally occurring variation in mitochondrial function in Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Mean mitochondrial state 3 respiration rate, measured as oxygen consumption (pmol/s* mg of protein). Mitochondria were sourced from the thorax and respiration was measured in vitro. State 3 respiration occurs when protons re-enter the mitochondrial matrix in the presence of ADP, which results in the production of ATP. Higher values indicate higher respiration rates.
Authors: P Jumbo-Lucioni, S Bu, ST Harbison, JC Slaughter…
Title: Nuclear genomic control of naturally occurring variation in mitochondrial function in Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Mean mitochondrial state 3 respiration rate, measured as oxygen consumption (pmol/s* mg of protein). Mitochondria were sourced from the thorax and respiration was measured in vitro. State 3 respiration occurs when protons re-enter the mitochondrial matrix in the presence of ADP, which results in the production of ATP. Higher values indicate higher respiration rates.
Authors: P Jumbo-Lucioni, S Bu, ST Harbison, JC Slaughter…
Title: Nuclear genomic control of naturally occurring variation in mitochondrial function in Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Mean mitochondrial state 4 respiration rate, measured as oxygen consumption (pmol/s* mg of protein). Mitochondria were sourced from the thorax and respiration was measured in vitro. State 4 respiration occurs when protons leak into the mitochondrial matrix in the absence of ADP, which is required for ATP synthase. Higher values indicate higher respiration rates.
Authors: P Jumbo-Lucioni, S Bu, ST Harbison, JC Slaughter…

Trait description: Mean adult abdomen length, when reared at 28C. Higher values indicate larger flies.
Authors: E Lafuente, D Duneau, P Beldade
Title: Genetic basis of thermal plasticity variation in Drosophila melanogaster body size
Diet: 45 gr. molasses, 75gr sugar, 70gr cornmeal, 20 gr. Yeast extract, 10 gr. Agar, 1100 ml water and 25 ml of Niapagin 10%

Reference: Lafuente, Duneau and Beldade (2018) PLOS Genetics
Trait description: Flies were reared at 18C and 28C, after which adult abdomen lengths were measured. Reaction norms for each DGRP line were calculated using the linear model lm (Size ~ Temperature). The absolute value of the slope is a measurement of thermal sensitivity, describing the magnitude of the plastic response to temperature. Higher values indicate greater thermal plasticity.
Authors: E Lafuente, D Duneau, P Beldade
Title: Genetic basis of thermal plasticity variation in Drosophila melanogaster body size

Trait description: The critical thermal minimum (CT min), which is defined as the temperature at which a complete cessation of movement is observed as a result of the fly entering chill coma. Egg-to-adult development occurred at 23C. Higher values indicate a higher CT min.
Title: Environmental variation partitioned into separate heritable components

Trait description: Flies were reared at five different temperatures during development, after which adult critical thermal minimums (CT min) were measured. Developmental stability across environments is the consistency of within-environment variation in CT min across environments. The authors calculate this by taking the highest coefficient of variation (CV) in CT min at any rearing temperature, minus the lowest CV at any other given rearing temperature. Lower values indicate greater developmental stability across rearing temperatures.
Title: Environmental variation partitioned into separate heritable components

Trait description: Flies were reared at fiev different temperatures during development, after which adult critical thermal minimums were measured (CT min). Reaction norms for each DGRP line were calculated using the linear model lm (CTmin ~ Rearing temperature). The absolute value of the slope provides a measure of the plastic response to temperature. Higher values indicate greater thermal plasticity.
Title: Environmental variation partitioned into separate heritable components

Trait description: Flies were reared at fiev different temperatures during development, after which adult critical thermal minimums (CT min) were measured. Reaction norms for each DGRP line were calculated using the linear model lm (CTmin ~ Rearing temperature). The standard error of the slope provides a measure of the extent to which the same genotype can produce the same plastic response consistently. Higher values indicate greater variance in thermal plasticity.
Title: Environmental variation partitioned into separate heritable components

Trait description: Flies were reared at five different temperatures during development, after which adult critical thermal minimums were measured. This trait captures how consistently a genotype produces the same phenotype at a given rearing temperature. Higher values indicate greater variance in phenotype within a rearing temperature.
Title: Environmental variation partitioned into separate heritable components

Trait description: Mean knockdown of adults, four hours after vials were inoculated with 0.5 ug/ml of DDT. Knockdown is defined as either flies permanently seen to be in a prone position with jolting movement of legs or wings, or a prolonged inability to right themselves from a prone position. DDT is a historically used pesticide that targets the voltage gated sodium channel, resulting in uncontrolled nerve firing. Higher values indicate greater susceptiibility to DDT.
Title: Insights into DDT resistance from the drosophila melanogaster genetic reference panel

Trait description: Mean survival of adults, 24 hours after vials were inoculated with 0.5 ug/ml of DDT. This is a historically used pesticide that targets the voltage gated sodium channel, resulting in uncontrolled nerve firing. Higher values indicate greater susceptiibility to DDT.

Trait description: Mean PC1 score for posterior lobe shape, calculated from 200 Fourier coefficients. Title: Genome-Wide Association Study on Male Genital Shape and Size in Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Mean PC2 score for posterior lobe shape, calculated from 200 Fourier coefficients. Title: Genome-Wide Association Study on Male Genital Shape and Size in Drosophila melanogaster

Trait description: Mean number of L1 larvae produced by females aged 5-6 days over a 24h period. For each replicate measurement, 5 DGRP females were housed with standardised mates and opposite-sex competitors (15 males and 10 females, giving an overall population size of 30 and 1:1 sex ratio). Fitness was estimated on the latent scale from a generalised linear mixed model, and is scaled to have a mean of zero and unit variance.

Authors: MK Zwoinska, LR Rodrigues, J Slate…
Title: Phenotypic responses to and genetic architecture of sterility following exposure to sub-lethal temperature during development
Diet: 10 L: 9 L water, 720 g cornmeal, 162 g dried yeast, 90 g soya flour, 720 g malt extract, 360 g molasses, 72 g agar, 36 mL propionic acid, and 225 mL of 10% Nipagin

Reference: Zwoinska et al (2020) Frontiers in Genetics
Trait description: Mean slope of the change in male fertility (the proportion of males that produced viable larvae), between 25C, 27C and 29C rearing conditions. Lower slope values indicate a greater decrease in fertility with an increase in temperature. This is a measure of thermal susceptibility.
